<br>
My rules for threads are these:<br>
<br>
1) Spam and obscenities are moved to the forum equivalent of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>/dev/null</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
2) Inappropriate topics in GENERAL are noted, usually with references to the appropriate forum, often a list of relevant threads, and more recently a short summary of the consensus regarding that subject.<br>
3) DUPLICATE inappropriate threads in GENERAL are locked.<br>
4) Inappropriate threads are moved to the correct forum when they age past the first page.<br>
<br>
I usually moderate in small chunks of time during the day, or occasionally I get a solid hour or so in the early morning or the late evening.<br>
<br>
As much as I love Graffe's, I think it is poorly moderated.  Everything is in GENERAL, there are too many duplicate threads, relevent threads are hard to find, no one uses the appropriate forums, and disrespect is far too tolerated.  Too many posters there seem incapable of posting a contrary opinion without demeaning their opponents.<br>
<br>
As for the visual spell effects thread, I admit to having to think to decide where it belonged.  I decided that USER INTERFACE seemed appropriate, since it is most literally a feature of the USER INTERFACE.<br>
<br>
Often forums have implied secondary topics that fall under their domain.  For example, the QUEST forum seems the most appropriate place to put threads about faction.<br>
<br>
But it is not always obvious.  Questions about pet weapons are sometimes about the pet, and sometimes about the spell itself.  Research is clearly a skill, but it is used to obtain spells, and what if someone asks, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;How do I obtain this spell?&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Likewise, is pet cannibalization a pet thread or a skill thread?  Where do I put threads about raiding?  Equipment?  The Hunt?<br>
<br>
There will be a consolidation of forums with the move, and hopefully better tools for organizing them.<br>
<br>
I am always open to feedback, and willing to discuss policy publicly, or privately through e-mail.<br>
<br>
